**Abstract:**
Extensive working notes dated January 30, 1992, titled "Fronesis and Sofia," engaging with Gauthier's commentary on the Nicomachean Ethics. The document argues that phronesis is not knowledge in any sense if by knowledge we mean what Aristotle following Plato understands. It develops an extended critique of Aristotle's attempt to reduce deliberative human capacity to knowledge, arguing there is an internal contradiction in Aristotle between his efforts to escape Platonic intellectualism and his continued subordination of practical to contemplative reason. The document develops an alternative view based on De Motu Animalium where the distinction between knowledge and desire does not appear.

**AI Recommendation:** Central research notes developing critique of Greek practical reason; foundational for understanding the author's alternative anthropology.

